1. d6! (1. Kd1? Nb4 2. Rh5 Kb7) (1. Nd4? Nb4 2. Rh5 Kb7) 1… exd6 (1… Kb7 leads to a technically lost endgame, e.g. 2. Nd4 exd6 3. Ke2 c2 (3… Ne7 4. Nc2) 4. Nxc2 Nc3+ 5. Kd3 Nd5 6. Ne3) 2. 1. b4!! A paradoxical move, giving Black a passed pawn in an already critical position. (1. Kc1? Qc6+ 2. Kb1 Qg6+ 3. Ka1 Qf6 4. Kb1 b5 5. Kc2 (5. Ka1 Qf1+ 6. Ka2 Qxf7+) (5. Ka2 Qxf7+) (5. Kc1 Qxh6+) 5… Qg6+ 6. Kc3 Qf6+ 7. Kc2 b4 8. axb4 Qg6+ 9. Kc3 (9. Kd1 Qb1+?) 9… Qc6+) 1… axb3 2. a4! (2. Kc3? Qf3+! 3. Kb2 Qf6+ 4. Kb1 Qf5+ 5. Ka1 Qe5+) 2… Qa5+ ( After 2… b2 3. Kc2 Qxa4+ 4. Kxb2 Black cannot win ) 3. Kd3! (3. Kd1? Qh5+! 4. Kc1 Qxh6+) (3. Ke2? Qe5+! 4. Kd3 Qf6! 5. Kd2 Qxh6+) (3. Kc1 Qc3+ 4. Kd1 Qf6 ) 3… Qf5+ (3… Qd5+ 4. Kc3! Qe5+ 5. Kxb3 positional draw ) 4. Kc3! Qf6+ 5. Kd3! Qd6+ 6. Kc3! Qe7 7. Kb2! Qf6+ 8. Kb1! (8. Ka3? b2 9. Ka2 Qxf7+) 8… b2 (8… Qd6 9. Kb2! Qe7 10. Kc3! (10. Kb1? Qf6!) 10… Qf6+ 11. Kd3! positional draw ) 9. Kc2! (9. Ka2? Qxf7+) 9… Qf2+ 10. Kb1 Qf6 11. Kc2 positional draw 1/2-1/2.

Helmut Waelzel. “White king in the center or on the kingside would lose one of the pawns d7, f7, h6 with check, so it needs exile on the queenside. There, for reasons of Zugzwang also, squares b2 and a3 are needed, a plan that cannot be delayed. A shocking key! Astonishing, that Black can not make use neither of the passed pawn itself nor of squares c2 and a2 of this queen. White king is manoevering against black queen, including quiet moves and even Zugzwang (position after 5.Kd3! is one, with thematic try 5.Ke2?, position after 8.Kb1! would be another, apparently withoug try).”

Ryo Shiomi (editor): “Black has more material, but White is the one to play for a win with his supeior K. After the preparatory 1. b4!, 2. g6! is the breakthrough we want to see! After some resistance from Black, 5. e4! ~ 6. e5! is the practial way to win the R endgame.”

Mattison +0133.12h3a6 (1922). Correction

Date: 2024, October 22

File: Mattison1922.pgn

Study no. 47 (Table 1)

The suspected cook by John Nunn is indeed a cook according to tablebase. The correction by Garcia is incorrect for the same reason: the Q-bn ending is lost. The additional black pawn on h4 gives black just enough counterplay.
